We live blogged the  U.S. stock market\’s action on Monday. You can read a wrap of pre-market actions here and get a compact rundown of the stock market in Market Snapshot.Good morning.Stocks are mostly lower in the early going, with the S&P 500 pulling back from Friday’s record close.Reports of weaker-than-expected Chinese exports are getting much of the blame. Equities in Asia closed sharply lower today.SPX -4 pointsDow -50 pointsNasdaq -6 pointsBoeing    /quotes/zigman/220026/delayed /quotes/nls/ba BA    is helping push the Dow lower.It’s the worst-performing Dow component so far today, last down about 2%.  There’s been more trouble for the aircraft maker’s 787 — news of cracks in the wings of some planes.Photo credit: Getty ImagesAnother Dow component with news today is McDonald’s   /quotes/zigman/233369/delayed /quotes/nls/mcd MCD   , which reported a global drop in monthly same-store sales.U.S. sales were down 1.4%. Dow Jones Market Talk emphasized the domestic decline follows drops in December and January, and these performances are “concerning of course since the US remains far and away MCD’s biggest market.”Shares in McDonald’s were last down 0.3% — not a big drop, but still a drop.Photo credit: BloombergThe S&P 500 has picked itself up off its session low, but it’s still in negative territory. The benchmark index was last down 0.1%.The Dow fell out of the gate and has basically moved sideways. The blue-chip index was down 0.3% at last check.The Nasdaq has been dancing around the break-even mark, at times showing small gains, at times showing small losses. The tech-heavy index was last up 0.1%.While the S&P 500 eked out another record close on Friday, Colin Cieszynski doesn’t sound impressed.The senior analyst at CMC Markets apparently would have preferred a finish above 1,880.He writes in a note today:“SPX500 failed to hold a new high Friday above 1,880 and continues to roll over today. A negative RSI divergence suggests uptrend weakening. Initial support appears in the 1,850 to 1,855 previous resistance zone followed by 1,830.”In his note this morning, CMC’s Cieszynski also has an interesting take on McDonald’s   /quotes/zigman/233369/delayed /quotes/nls/mcd MCD    same-store sales falling 0.3% for February.The news “can be seen as a potentially positive indicator for the global economy,” he writes.“Just as more people tend to eat at McDonalds in recessions, the same people may elect to eat at more expensive restaurants when they have more money or feel more secure about the economy,” the analyst says.And for more about McDonald’s, check out what MarketWatch’s Catey Hill has to say about how the fast-food giant could become more like its old friend Chipotle   /quotes/zigman/395806/delayed /quotes/nls/cmg CMG    — namely by getting involved in the customization trend.Photo credit: BloombergThe bananas industry — that’s the latest sector with M&A news, joining cable, pharma, jewelry.Overall, the merger activity could show the mood in corporate boardrooms is optimistic. They’re making deals there rather than hunkering down.Chiquita   /quotes/zigman/300672/delayed /quotes/nls/cqb CQB    is merging with Ireland-based fruit company Fyffes in an all-stock transaction worth $1 billion, the two companies said Monday.Chiquita was last up 13%.Photo credit: Associated PressStocks are at fresh session lows, really retreating after last week’s gains.Weaker-than-expected data from China did not help this morning, after the official report showed a surprise drop in exports last month. Some analysts says data might be distorted by the celebration of Lunar New Year, however. Ongoing tension between Ukraine and Russia is also weighing on risky assets – as gold and Treasurys are gaining, while oil and equity markets are falling.SPX 

