pointing economic news from China and worries about Ukraine are weighing on stocks to start the week. But it’s just a pause, according to portfolio manager George Young of the Villere Balanced Fund.A quick market update – stocks are firmly in red. SPX -0.32%DJIA -0.45COMP -0.37%In other markets today:Treasury prices swung higher, but traded in an narrow range ahead of debt supply.Gold prices settled 0.2% higher at $1,341.50 per troy ounce.Oil futures drop more than 1% as downbeat data from China cut into prospects for energy demand.The bitcoin exchange Mt. Gox filed for Chapter 15 bankruptcy in the U.S. on Sunday in an attempt to seek relief from pending litigation in the U.S, including the class-action lawsuit. The exchange filed for bankruptcy in Japan on Feb. 28. and disclosed it had lost  thousands of bitcoins belonging to customers. An emergency hearing is scheduled for Monday in Texas on Mt. Gox’s filing. Read more.  Meanwhile, a linguistic analysis requested by Forbes suggested that Dorian Prentice Satoshi Nakamoto, who was identified as the creator of bitcoin by Newsweek, is likely not the correct person. Alexion Pharmaceuticals 

