 another global kingpin in the fruit distribution business, in a $1.07 billion, all-stock deal. The deal creates the world’s biggest banana business, with sales of about $4.6 billion.By joining forces, the combined ChiquitaFyffes claims it will knock down operating costs by about $40 million a year.But the move also knocks down Chiquita’s taxes, since it’s hitching itself to a company domiciled in Dublin.Ireland isn’t exactly a tax shelter, but it’s close. Companies based there pay a 12.5% corporate tax rate compared with the (official) rate of up to 35% in the United States.Several U.S. companies have already figured out the Ireland advantage. Drug maker Perrigo 

